{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"CONTAINER review (G4 — child consistency), parent c81c-cbcd-17a0-43d2 (plan-review fan-out optimization). Reviewed THIS child (S3 — parallelize container fan-out + warm-then-fan-out + budget-cap fix) WHOLE against the complete sibling roster (S1 0250, S2 c6e5, S4 98c6, S5 1762, S6 da34) and the parent. Walked all 7 cross-child interaction modes. NO G4 FINDINGS — clean pairing.\n\n7-mode walk:\n- IMPLICIT SHARED STATE: S3, S4, S5 all touch the sizing.py container-cost projection (len(cont)*n_children*COST_AGENT, sizing.py:206) and the _run_container call structure (pass1.py). Real shared state, but the parent Sequencing note + DAG (S3->S4->S5) STRICTLY serialize it (\"S4/S5's sizing.py container-cost projections are only correct AFTER S3's 'container never shed' + cost-model fix lands\"). S3 is foundational/first; each later landing layers a correct projection on the prior (S3 fixes base cost + never-shed; S4 -> N; S5 -> <N). No contradiction.\n- CONFLICTING ASSUMPTIONS: S3's warm-then-fan-out premise (warm WRITES the prefix, fan-out READS it) is exactly what S1 delivers and S1's de-risk E2 empirically confirmed (cold-concurrent x3 => 3 writes/0 reads; warm-first => 0 writes/3 reads). No sibling assumes G3/G4 can be shed; S3's \"container NEVER shed\" is consistent with the parent fidelity AC and with S4/S5's eval-gating (which assume the container always runs). No conflict.\n- DEPENDENCY GAP: S1 (0250) blocks ba7e (dep link present); ba7e blocks S4 (98c6) (dep link present). Byte-stability (an S1 AC) is the upstream precondition S3's warm-then-fan-out relies on; correctly ordered. No gap.\n- SCOPE OVERLAP: S3 fences out S1/S4/S5 and each fences S3 reciprocally. Shared files pass1.py (_run_container) and sizing.py are split as SERIAL layered edits under strict S3->S4->S5 (S3 builds the new pool + warm + never-shed/cost-model fix; S4/S5 take the sizing projection N->/<N; S5 adds bin-packing inside the same structure), not concurrent contradictory ownership. Benign under ANTI-FP.\n- ORDERING VIOLATION: none — S3 is correctly the HEAD of the S3->S4->S5 chain and the first to touch the shared projection; the Sequencing note pins this.\n- CONSUMER IMPACT: S3's \"container criteria are NEVER shed; the cap bounds only overlay/agent spend\" + the cost-model correction is consumed (not contradicted) by S4/S5's projections and by the parent budget AC. Producer->consumer is DAG-ordered. Consistent.\n- RESIDUAL REFERENCES: no sibling carries a stale contract against a design S3 removes. S3's budget-cap change removes the shed-G3/G4 path; no sibling references the centrality-inversion or assumes container shedding. Consistent.\n\nNon-G4 note (intra-child editorial only, below the cross-child/high-confidence threshold — recorded, not a finding): the child's \"What\" bullet and original ACs still carry the SUPERSEDED framing — \"await its first streamed token\" (the runner is non-streaming) and \"Fix the budget cap that scales with centrality (sizing.py base*(1+centrality))\" implying centrality-inversion. The child's own Remediation explicitly reverses BOTH (warm = first real pairing to completion; do NOT invert centrality — instead never-shed container + fix the cost model). These are stale body/AC labels superseded by the same ticket's Remediation, not a cross-child inconsistency; they read benignly under the ANTI-FP filter."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578812408554001,"uuid":"10efbc59-b108-498a-bcb7-9ace5c7f9448"}